title: 4. Branches of the Brachial Plexus Within the Axilla

vectorData.altText: 17A   Branches of the Brachial Plexus Within the Axilla

The suprascapular nerve innervates two of the rotator cuff muscles, the supraspinatus and the infraspinatus     .     
Recall that because the rotator cuff muscles, as a group, hold the head of the humerus in the glenoid fossa, damage to the suprascapular nerve can cause instability of the glenohumeral joint, and an increased risk of dislocation.
The long thoracic nerve innervates the serratus anterior muscle     . Because the serratus anterior muscle holds the scapula against the thoracic wall, lesion of the long thoracic nerve causes “winged scapula”      .
